{{refimprove|date=October 2016}}
'''Failure of consideration''' is a technical [[legal]] term referring to situations in which one person confers a benefit upon another upon some condition or basis ("[[consideration]]") which fails to materialise or subsist. It is also referred to as "failure of basis".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://epublications.bond.edu.au/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1479&context=blr |author=Camp T |title=Restitution on a Partial Failure of Basis}} (2016) 28 Bond Law Review 21.</ref> It is an '[[English unjust enrichment law|unjust factor]]' for the purposes of the [[English unjust enrichment law|law of unjust enrichment]]. Where there is a "total failure of consideration" the claimant can seek restitution of the benefit by bringing an action in unjust enrichment against the defendant. Historically speaking, this was as a [[Quasi-contract|quasi-contractual]] claim known as an [[Money had and received|action for money had and received to the plaintiff's use]] for a consideration that wholly failed. The orthodox view is that it is necessary for any relevant contract to be ineffective, for example because it is discharged for [[Breach of contract|breach]], [[Void (law)|void]] ''ab initio'' (from the beginning) or [[Frustration in English law|frustrated]]. However, it will be available on a subsisting contract where it does not undermine the contractual allocation of risk.<ref>{{cite AustLII|NSWCA|153|2007|litigants=Coshott v Lenin |courtname=auto}}.</ref>

Failure of consideration is a highly technical area of law. Particular areas of controversy include:
*Whether the failure of the consideration must be 'total',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.austlii.edu.au/au/journals/UWALawRw/2006/6.pdf |last=Tarrant |first=J |title=Total Failure of Consideration}} (2006) 33(1) University of Western Australia Law Review 132.</ref> and the scope and meaning of such a requirement;
*Whether 'consideration' refers not only to bargained-for counter-performance by the defendant, but also a legal or factual state of affairs;
*Whether this ground of restitution only applies to money claims or also extends to non-money benefits (e.g., [[Personal property|chattels]], services);  
*Whether this ground of restitution can be relied upon by a contract-breaker;
*Whether the (now ineffective) contract has any impact upon (a) the availability of a claim; or (b) the valuation of any such claim;  
*Whether a failure of consideration can also generate [[Unjust enrichment#Remedies for unjust enrichment: personal and proprietary restitution|proprietary remedies]] (e.g., a resulting trust);  
*Whether a claimant can elect to terminate a contract for breach and escape a 'bad bargain' by suing in unjust enrichment on the ground of total failure of consideration.  

==Cases==
*''[[Goss v Chilcott]]'' <ref>{{cite BAILII| litigants=[[Goss v Chilcott]] |year=1996 |court=UKPC |num=17 |courtname=auto |juris=New Zealand}}.</ref>
*''Rowland v Divall'', 1922 <ref>[http://casebrief.me/casebriefs/rowland-v-divall/ Case Brief: Rowland v. Divall (1922)], accessed 22 October 2016</ref>
*''Giedo van der Garde BV v Force India Formula One Team Ltd.'', 2010 <ref>{{cite BAILII |court=EWHC |division=QB |year=2010 |num= 2373 |litigants=Giedo van der Garde BV v Force India Formula One Team Ltd |courtname=auto}}.</ref>

==Further reading==
*Andrew Burrows, ''The Law of Restitution'' (3rd ed, 2011).
*Graham Virgo, ''Principles of the Law of Restitution'' (3rd ed, 2015).
*Keith Mason, John Carter, Gregory Tolhurst, ''Mason & Carter's Restitution Law in Australia'' (2nd ed, 2008).

