{{Other people|George Mason}} {{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}} {{Infobox military person |name = George Thomson Mason |birth_date = 17 August 1818 |death_date = {{death date and age|1846|04|26|1818|08|17|df=yes}} |birth_place = [[Gunston Hall]], [[Fairfax County, Virginia]] |death_place= [[Fort Brown]], [[Texas]] |image = |caption = | allegiance = {{flag|United States|1845}} |branch = [[United States Army]] |serviceyears = 1838&ndash;1846 |rank = {{Dodseal|USA second lieutenant|25}} [[Second lieutenant#United States|Second Lieutenant]] |commands = |unit= [[2d Stryker Cavalry Regiment|2nd Dragoon Regiment]] |battles = [[Mexican–American War]] |awards = }} '''George Thomson Mason''' (17 August 1818 &ndash; 26 April 1846)<ref name=GH>{{cite web | url=http://www.gunstonhall.org/library/masonweb/p2.htm#i62 | title=George Thomson Mason | date=| accessdate=2008-03-21 | publisher= Gunston Hall | author=Gunston Hall}}</ref> was a [[United States Army]] [[Second Lieutenant (United States)#United States|Second Lieutenant]] killed in the [[Thornton Affair]] during the [[Mexican–American War]]. Mason was a [[kinship|scion]] of the prominent [[Mason family|Mason political family]] of [[Virginia]].
==Early life and education== Mason was born on 17 August 1818 at [[Gunston Hall]] in [[Fairfax County, Virginia|Fairfax County]], [[Virginia]].<ref name=GH/><ref name=WG>{{cite book |title=Wood Genealogy and History |last=Allison |first=Edna Finney |authorlink= |coauthors= |year= 1971 |publisher= |location= |isbn= |page= |pages= |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5wFgAAAAMAAJ}}</ref> He was the fourth child and second-eldest son of [[George Mason VI]] (11 August 1786&ndash;21 August 1834) and his wife Elizabeth Thomson Mason (1789&ndash;2 September 1821).<ref name=GH/> Mason was a great-grandson of [[George Mason]] (11 December 1725&ndash;7 October 1792), a [[Founding Fathers of the United States|Founding Father of the United States]].<ref name=GH/>
Mason was a student in the [[United States Military Academy]] at [[West Point, New York|West Point]], [[New York (state)|New York]] between 1 July 1838 and 1 July 1842.<ref name=GH/><ref name=WG/><ref name=FM>{{cite web |url=http://www.accd.edu/pac/faculty/rhines/StudentProjects/2007/Mason/Mason,%20Texas.htm |title=Mason, Texas |date=2007-04-10 |accessdate=2008-03-21 |publisher=The Alamo Community Colleges |author=Ray Montez |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090828034545/http://www.accd.edu/pac/faculty/rhines/StudentProjects/2007/Mason/Mason%2C%20Texas.htm |archivedate=28 August 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref>
==Military career== Upon his graduation from West Point, Mason was promoted in the [[United States Army]] to [[Brevet (military)|Brevet]] [[Second Lieutenant (United States)#United States|Second Lieutenant]] in the [[2nd U.S. Dragoons]].<ref name=ZT>{{cite web|url=http://www.library.ci.corpus-christi.tx.us/mexicanwar/masongt.htm |title=George T. Mason |year=2004 |accessdate=2008-03-21 |publisher= Corpus Christi Public Libraries |author=Corpus Christi Public Libraries |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080305204908/http://www.library.ci.corpus-christi.tx.us/MexicanWar/masongt.htm |archivedate=5 March 2008 }}</ref> Mason then served at the School of Cavalry Practice at [[Carlisle Barracks]] in [[Carlisle, Pennsylvania|Carlisle]], [[Pennsylvania]].<ref name=ZT/> Following his service at Carlisle Barracks, Mason served at [[Fort Jesup]] in [[Louisiana]] between 1842 and 1843.<ref name=WG/><ref name=FM/><ref name=ZT/> From there, Mason served in an expedition to the [[Arkansas River]] in 1843.<ref name=ZT/> At [[Fort Leavenworth]], Mason was transferred to the [[1st Cavalry Regiment (United States)|1st U.S. Dragoons]] on 6 March 1843 and served at the fort between 1843 and 1844.<ref name=ZT/> Mason departed from Fort Leavenworth to participate in Scouting to Pawnee Villages in 1844 and then returned to Fort Leavenworth where he was again made a Second Lieutenant in the 2nd U.S. Dragoons on 13 September 1844.<ref name=ZT/> Mason served in Fort Jesup between 1844 and 1845 and in the Military Occupation of Texas between 1845 and 1846.<ref name=WG/><ref name=FM/><ref name=ZT/>
Mason died on 26 April 1846 at age 27 near [[Fort Brown]], Texas, 25 miles from [[Brownsville, Texas|Brownsville]].<ref name=GH/><ref name=FM/><ref name=ZT/><ref name=VM>{{cite book |title=The Virginia Magazine of History and Biography |last=Virginia Historical Society |first= |authorlink= |coauthors= |year= 1896 |publisher=Virginia Historical Society |location= |isbn= |page= |pages= |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o78RAAAAYAAJ}}</ref> Mason died of injuries sustained in the [[Thornton Affair]] (also known as the Skirmish of [[La Rosita, Texas|La Rosita]]), considered the first battle of the [[Mexican–American War]].<ref name=FM/><ref name=ZT/><ref name=VM/> The two squadrons under the command of Captains May and Seth Thornton had marched out to reconnoiter Mexican movements when Thornton's command ran into a larger force of 500 Mexicans near La Rosita, and became surrounded.<ref name=WT>{{cite web|url=http://home.att.net/~w.tomtschik/13.html |title=2nd Dragoons in the Mexican War |date= |accessdate=2008-03-21 |publisher=Robert E. Lee Fought For God And Country Too, A Great American! |author=W. Tomtschik }}{{dead link|date=January 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Mason and eight enlisted men were killed, along with two enlisted wounded.<ref name=WT/>
==Honours== It is believed that Fort Mason in [[Mason, Texas|Mason]], Texas was named in honour of Mason.<ref name=FM/><ref name=TSHA>{{cite web | url=http://www.tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/qbf34 | title=FORT MASON | date=2008-01-17 | accessdate=2008-03-21 | publisher=Texas State Historical Association | author=Julius E. DeVos}}</ref> Although the fort's history dates as far back to 1845, official records indicate that Fort Mason was not established until 6 July 1851.<ref name=FM/><ref name=TSHA/>
==Ancestry== {{ahnentafel |collapsed=yes |align=center |boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc; |boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9; |boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc; |boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc; |boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe; |1= 1. '''George Thomson Mason''' |2= 2. [[George Mason VI]] |3= 3. Elizabeth Thomson Mason |4= 4. [[George Mason V]] |5= 5. Elizabeth Mary Anne Barnes Hooe |6= 6. [[Thomson Mason (1759–1820)|Thomson Mason]] |7= 7. Sarah McCarty Chichester |8= 8. [[George Mason|George Mason IV]] |9= 9. Ann Eilbeck |10= 10. Gerard Hooe |11= 11. Sarah Barnes |12= 12. [[George Mason|George Mason IV]] (= 8) |13= 13. Ann Eilbeck (= 9) |14= 14. Richard Chichester |15= 15. Sarah McCarty |16= 16. [[George Mason III]] |17= 17. Ann Stevens Thomson |18= 18. William Eilbeck |19= 19. Sarah Edgar |20= 20. John Hooe |21= 21. Anne Fowke Alexander |22= 22. Richard Barnes |23= 23. Penelope Manly |24= 24. [[George Mason III]] (= 16) |25= 25. Ann Stevens Thomson (= 17) |26= 26. William Eilbeck (= 18) |27= 27. Sarah Edgar (= 19) |28= 28. Richard Chichester |29= 29. Ellen Ball |30= 30. Daniel McCarty |31= 31. Sinah Ball }}
