'''Sir Michael Edwardes''' (born 11 October 1930)<ref>{{cite web|title=Sir Michael Edwardes|url=http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/browse/e/16007/Michael%20Owen+EDWARDES.aspx|work=Debretts|accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref>  is a British-South African business executive.

==Biography==
Edwardes matriculated from [[St. Andrew's College (Grahamstown, South Africa)|St. Andrew's College]] in 1947 before graduating from [[Rhodes University]]. He began his career in 1951 with the [[Chloride Group]]. He went on in 1966 to serve as the general manager of Alkaline Batteries, one of the groups operating companies at Redditch, Worcestershire UK. He later joined the Chloride main board and became Chief Executive in 1971 and remained in that position until 1977  

He was appointed to the UK's [[National Enterprise Board]], a [[QUANGO]] whose role was to provide financing to large UK state-owned enterprises (or nationalized industries), including the country's ailing motor giant, [[British Leyland]], when it was established in 1975.  

In 1977 he was appointed as chief executive of [[British Leyland]], and within two weeks he became chairman as the company's board was 'pruned' from 13 to 7 members.<ref name=Motor197711>{{cite magazine| authorlink=Roger Bell (Ed)|title=MotorWeek: Surgery for survival|magazine=[[The Motor (magazine)|Motor]]|volume=152: nbr 3919|page=2|date=26 November 1977}}</ref> In 1979 he was knighted in the [[Queen's Birthday Honours]].<ref name=Motor1979>{{cite magazine|authorlink=Unsigned|title=Newsflashes|magazine=[[The Motor (magazine)|Motor]]|volume=155 nbr 4002|page=4|date=23 June 1979}}</ref>  

The next year, in 1980 he attracted criticism for a speech to the CBI Conference in which he said, "If the Cabinet do not have the wit and imagination to reconcile our industrial needs with the fact of [[North Sea oil]], they would do better to leave the bloody stuff in the ground."{{sfn|Edwardes|1983}}

His tenure with British Leyland lasted until 1982, when he was replaced by [[Harold Musgrove]].

In 1982, on his retirement from British Leyland as CEO, Sir Michael Edwardes was presented with a British Racing Green Jaguar XJS.  He later had this car shipped to South Africa, where he used it for board meetings at General Motors South Africa in 1988.

In 1984, he became Chairman of [[International Computers Limited|ICL]], but resigned six months later when the company was acquired by [[Standard Telephones and Cables|STC]].

Edwardes wrote ''Back from the Brink'', a book which discusses his experiences at [[British Leyland]].

He donated over [[South African Rand|R]]500,000 to [[St. Andrew's College (Grahamstown, South Africa)|St. Andrew's College]] in 2005. {{Citation needed|date=August 2010}}

