[[File:Sir George Burns.jpg|thumb|right|An etching of Sir George Burns]]
'''Sir George Burns, 1st Baronet''' (10 December 1795 – 2 June 1890) was a [[Scotland|Scottish]] [[shipping]] [[business magnate|magnate]].

Burns was born in [[Glasgow]], the son of [[John Burns (minister)|Rev John Burns]] (1744–1839),  a [[Presbyterian]] [[minister of religion|minister]]. George was the younger brother of [[James Burns (1789-1871)]], with whom he formed a [[partnership]], [[J. & G. Burns]]. Together, they started sailing ships between Glasgow and [[Liverpool]], as well as across the [[Atlantic]] to [[Canada]] and the [[United States]]. J. & G. Burns set up the regular [[Steamboat|steamer]] service to the [[Inner Hebrides|Inner]] and [[Outer Hebrides]]. This was sold to David Hutcheson & Co in 1851, and by the mid-1870s, it formed the basis of [[David MacBrayne Ltd]], which today operates as [[Caledonian MacBrayne]] across the west coast of [[Scotland]].

Burns was party to the consolidation of a number of companies, including the [[British and North American Royal Mail Steam Packet Company]], into the [[Cunard Line]], which had been begun by Sir [[Samuel Cunard]]. The Cunard Line merged with the [[White Star Line]] in 1936, and was to launch [[Ocean liner|liner]]s such as the [[RMS Queen Mary|RMS ''Queen Mary'']] (1936). Today it is a US-owned [[cruise ship|cruise]] company, which operated the famous [[RMS Queen Elizabeth 2|RMS ''Queen Elizabeth 2'']] (QE2).

In addition to his shipping interests, Burns was also one of the largest shareholders in [[Glasgow and South Western Railway|The Glasgow and South-Western Railway]]

Burns retired to [[Wemyss Bay]] in [[Renfrewshire (historic)|Renfrewshire]] ([[Inverclyde]]). He was made a [[baronet]] at age 94 in 1889,<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=25948 |date=25 June 1889 |page=3407}}</ref> the oldest ever recipient of the award. A devout [[Scottish Episcopal Church|Episcopalian]], Edwin Hodder wrote a [[hagiography]] of Burns, and J.J. Burnet's Inverclyde Church was instituted in the memory of Burns and his wife. [[John William Burns|John Burns]] (1829–1901), his eldest son, succeeded him in the baronetcy, became head of the [[Cunard Line|Cunard Company]] and was created a peer, under the title of [[Baron Inverclyde]], in 1897.

